column1: #Text=Swiss-German ( Schweizerdeutsch in Standard German ; some endonyms are Schwyzerdütsch , Schwiizertüütsch or Schwizertitsch ) is a broad category of Germanic dialects spoken in Switzerland .

#Text=These dialects are considerably different from German , especially as it happens in regard to those very phrases which a traveler needs : niceties , greetings , asking for stuff , getting directions , etc.
#Text=One of the key differences to getting by with Swiss German .
#Text=For example , " Fine , thank you " is Guet , merci ; with guet being the German word for good/fine , while merci is from the French " thank you " .
#Text=In addition , there are many pronunciation differences which separate Swiss-German from either language .
#Text=For example , the diphthong in Swiss-German " guet " versus the monophthong in High-German " gut " .
#Text=You are unlikely to have to learn Swiss-German , as all German-speaking Swiss educated in modern day schools are also able to speak standard German .
#Text=Nevertheless , saying a few words in Swiss-German will undoubtedly impress the locals .

#Text=Swiss German is different from Swiss Standard German ( Schweizer Hochdeutsch ) , which is a variant of standard German for formal speech and writing in Switzerland , with some vocabulary differences , such as das Tram ( " streetcar " , Straßenbahn or die Tram in standard German ) and Billett ( " ticket " , Fahrkarte , Fahrschein or Ticket in standard German ) .
#Text=Neither Swiss German nor Swiss Standard German use the Eszett ( ß ) .

#Text=Note that most of the following Swiss-German phrases and words are written as they would be pronounced by people living in the area around Bern , Basel , Zürich ( i. e. in the canton of Bern , etc. ) .
#Text=Whilst bernese dialect is widely understood in the Swiss-German part of Switzerland , it 's by no means " official " Swiss-German ( despite of the fact that Bern is the Swiss capital ) .
#Text=There is no standardized Swiss-German ( " Schwyzerdüütsch " ) , and it is standard
#Text=German that is an official language in Switzerland .
#Text=Remarkably , the native dialects spoken in the many Swiss-German cantons are clearly distinguishable by locals ( i. e. they can tell apart from the dialect in which canton somebody grew up ) .
#Text=Speaking Swiss-German is common for all people living in the Swiss-German part of Switzerland , independent of age or education .
#Text=For writing , standard German is mostly used , though Swiss-German dialect is particularly popular on informal writing ( e. g. in e-mail messages , SMS messages etc. ) .

#Text=With the ongoing globalization and immigration , mixing Swiss-German dialects with English ( quite often even with pseudo English ) or speaking so called " Jugo-Deutsch " ( German pronounced as immigrants coming from the former Yugoslavia region tend to pronounce it ) has also become trendy for youngsters .
#Text=For official documents , standard German is used .
#Text=The vowels in swiss german are unlike the english vowels closer to the german and latin pronunciations .
#Text=Hello , everyone ( formal ) : Grüezi mitenand ! [ Grea-tsi metta-nònd ] / Grüessech mitenang !
#Text=I lost my wallet ! ( ch , n , s = variants , depending on the dialect )
#Text=i(ch ) fühl mi(ch ) schlächt : I feel sick/not well/upset ( ch = variant )
#Text=i(ch ) mues öppis mälde : I have to/must report something ( ch = variant )
#Text=Hät 's da es Spital i de Nöchi ? : is there a hospital nearby ?
#Text=i(ch ) bi(n ) velore/mer sind verlore : I/we am/are lost ! ! ( ch , n = variant )
#Text=Can you please tell me where ... is ?
#Text=What time is it ? : Was isch für zit ?
#Text=Wie lang gohts bis ... ( How long does it take to ... )
#Text=Gäld / Bargäld , Stutz ( coll . ) , Stütz ( coll . ) : cash , money .
#Text=mit Bargäld bezahle ? : can I pay with cash ? pay with cash ?
#Text=Was koschtet das ? : how much is this/that ?
#Text=Das isch mir e chli z'tüür : That seems to be rather expensive ( more polite phrasing )
#Text=I(ch ) nimm das : I 'll take/buy it ( i pronounced like " e " in english )
#Text=I(ch ) möcht öppis anders : I would like something else .
#Text=Wo chan i(ch ) Gäld wächsle ? : Where can I change money ?
#Text=Wo isch de nächscht Bankomat ? : Where is the closest ATM ?
